The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Monday, August 02, 2004  Business Briefs																								 Calcutta, Aug. 1: The RPG group, promoters of power-utility major CESC Ltd, has reduced its holding in the company by 0.09 per cent during the first quarter of this financial year. The promoters stake, comprising those of the management group and families in the company, has come down by one lakh shares to 2.72 crore on June 30. This is 41.06 per cent of the total equity capital. On March 31, the promoters held 2.73 crore shares, or 41.15 per cent, sources said. However, the Goenkas stake has gone up by 2.79 per cent if the comparison is made on a year-on-a-year basis, instead of a quarterly time-frame.																								 New Delhi, Aug. 1: Tax collections have surged by 27 per cent to Rs 24,306 crore in the first quarter of this financial year mainly due to robust corporate earnings. However, the governments fiscal deficit has surged by almost 8 per cent to Rs 41,681 crore despite the growth in tax collection.																								 Hyderabad, Aug. 1: Shareholders of Global Trust Bank today sought political intervention to safeguard the investors interests. GTB Investors Association termed the merger of GTB with the Oriental Bank of Commerce as a political conspiracy.																								 New Delhi, Aug. 1: Auto exports rose 38.1 per cent in the first quarter of 2004-05. A total of 1.52 lakh units were shipped during the period, over 1.10 lakh units in the year-ago quarter, according to the data available with the SIAM.																								 New Delhi, Aug. 1: India Inc mobilised as much as Rs 12,000 crore in the first quarter of this financial year, the bulk of which came through debt, according to Prime Database.
